\begin{abstract}
This is a mathematical diversion to while away some time, and stimulate your brain. Try solving it before looking at the paper, as it states some basic equations and approaches quickly. The problem is stated below.

There is a vertical wall, and a horizontal floor. A box, measuring 1m x 1m x 1m lies on the floor, and is flush against the wall and the floor. The problem is actually in 2D, so you can ignore depth. Suppose there is a ladder, of length $c$, which is propped so that the top of the ladder touches the wall, the bottom touches the floor, and somewhere along its length it touches the corner of the box. The question is: determine $b$, the horizontal distance from the bottom of the box to the point at which the ladder meets the floor. You may assume $c=3$ if that helps. There are no tricks in the statement of this problem.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

I was introduced to the Ladder Problem when I first went to A-level
classes in mathematics in 1983. I attended at the Southend College of
Technology. It has since changed its name to South East Essex College
of Arts and Technology. My teacher in pure mathematics set the problem
for students to try to solve, although it was not part of the
curriculum. I spent many a bus ride trying to figure out its
solution. It is a pesky problem, because you would think it could be
expressed as a quadratic equation. Those are easy to solve. However,
whenever you try to construct equations for the problem, they end up
as quartics. Fortunately, there are general solutions to quartics, but
I did not know how to solve them. Eventually, the best I could do at
the time was to express the problem as an iterative equation which
could be solved approximately. It was only in 2014 that I tried to
solve the problem in earnest. Of course, we have the internet now, and
my education is more advanced, so I knew what I was looking for, and I
had hit on the idea of symmetry.

This article looks at two approaches to the problem: one taking the easy route by solving the problem numerically, and the second, taking a more satisfying route of assuming the resultant quartic can be factored as two quadratics, and exploring the assumption. Before we look at solutions, let me illustrate the ladder problem in the figure below. You can make use of the labelling that I have adopted. Below that is a theorem which expresses  the value $b$ in terms of $c$. You should make your own attempt at deriving the equation before looking at it.

