\begin{theorem}
$b$ and $c$ satisfy the equations
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:solve}
b^4 + 2 b ^3 + (2-c^2) b^2 + 2 b + 1 = 0
\end{equation}
\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
By definition, 
\begin{equation}
|P'Q|=b, |RQ| = c
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
|PP'| = |PR'| = |R'Q'| = |P'Q'| = 1.
\end{equation}

Also,
\begin{equation}
|PQ| = |PP'| + |P'Q| = 1+b
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
|PR| = |PR'| + |R'R| = 1 + |R'R|.
\end{equation}
By similar triangles
\begin{equation}
\frac{|R'R|}{|R'Q|} = \frac{|P'Q'|}{P'Q|},
\end{equation}
which simplifies to
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:rpr}
|R'R| = \frac{1}{b}.
\end{equation}

By Pythagorus' Theorem
\begin{equation}
|PQ|^2 + |PR|^2 = |RQ|^2 .
\end{equation}
Substituting in the values defined previously yields the equation
\begin{equation}
(1+b)^2 + (1+ \frac{1}{b})^2 = c^2.
\end{equation}
Multiply both sides of the equation by $b^2$, giving
\begin{equation}
b^2(1+b)^2 + (1+b)^2 = b^2c^2.
\end{equation}
Expand, giving
\begin{equation}
b^4+2b^3+b^2+b^2+2b+1=b^2c^2.
\end{equation}
Rearranging gives the required result.

\end{proof}


\section{Numerical solution}

The most straightforward way of solving the problem is to use iteration. We re-arrange \eqref{eq:solve} with $c=3$ to the form the iterative equation:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:iter}
b_{n+1} = \sqrt[4]{ - (2b_n ^3 -7 b_n ^2 + 2 b_n + 1)}.
\end{equation}
We take an initial guess at the solution, say $b_0 = 1$, and keep iterating \eqref{eq:iter} until convergence. We obtain the solution $b=1.49207$ to 4 dp. We expect there to be a different solution, but it turns our that $1.49207$ is the stable one, and that \eqref{eq:iter} does not  yield the other solution readily. However, we note that, due to the symmetry of the problem, another solution is 
$|R'R| = 1/b$ (equation \eqref{eq:rpr}), i.e. $0.6702$.



\section{Solution using intuition: quadratic factorisation}

My favourite way of solving the problem is to use intuition and guesswork. The problem seems to have a lot of \emph{symmetry} about it, as if there were a \emph{quadratic} trying to escape into the solution. Equation \eqref{eq:solve} also has a lot of symmetry to it, too.

Let us, therefore, \emph{assume} that it can be factored into two quadratics, and see where that leads us. Specifically, let us assume that there is a solution of the form
\begin{equation}
(b^2 + a_1b+1)(b^2+a_2b+1)=0
\end{equation}
for some $a_1$ and $a_2$ to be determined.

Expanding yields:
\begin{equation}
b^4 + (a_1+a_2)b^3 + (a_1 a_2 +2) b^2 + 1 =0.
\end{equation}
Equating co-efficients with \eqref{eq:solve} gives us
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:b3}
a_1+a_2 =2
\end{equation}
for co-efficients in $b^3$, and
\begin{equation}
a_1a_2+2=2-c^2
\end{equation}
for co-efficients in $b^2$, which in turn simplifies to
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:b2}
a_1a_2 = -c^2.
\end{equation}
Hence
\begin{equation}
a_2 = 1 \pm \sqrt{1+c^2}.
\end{equation}
Substitute back into \eqref{eq:b3} to obtain
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:a1}
a_1 = a_2 = 1\pm \sqrt{1+c^2}.
\end{equation}

Thus, it is sufficient to solve the equation
\begin{equation}
b^2 + a_1b +1 =0.
\end{equation}
This, of course, has solution
\begin{equation}
b = \frac{-a_1 \pm \sqrt{a_1 ^2 - 4a_1}}{2 a_1}.
\end{equation}
The full analytical expansion is messy, but in the case $c=3$, the solutions are -3.9063, -0.2560, 0.6702, 1.4907 to 4 dp. 


